headline.main: Inequality Has Actually Not Risen Since the Financial Crisis
headline.print_headline: Since the Financial Crisis, a Little Less Inequality

docs.abstract: David Leonhardt The Upshot column looks at report by Stephen J Rose of George Washington University showing that income inequality has not risen since financial crisis; findings, which were based on analysis of tax records and Congressional Budget Office statistics, suggest not only that income inequality is not inevitable, but that government policy has larger effects on issue than is commonly believed.

docs.lead_paragraph: Three-dimensional printers create inexpensive, striking prosthetics that hint at comic-book superpowers for children who are missing fingers.

headline.seo: 3-D Printing Prosthetic Hands That Are Anything but Ordinary

docs.abstract: Three-dimensional printers are useful for making striking and inexpensive prosthetic limbs for children, given that they outgrow replacement limbs too quickly for expensive, cutting- edge prosthetic devices to be worth investment; versatility of printers also allows for design of fantasy-inspired parts that are appealing to children.
docs.snippet: Three-dimensional printers create inexpensive, striking prosthetics that hint at comic-book superpowers for children who are missing fingers.

docs.lead_paragraph: The insolvency of CoOportunity Health raised the question of whether a major Affordable Care Act experiment in holding down insurance costs was in trouble beyond Iowa and Nebraska.

headline.main: Health Care Success for Midwest Co-op Proves Its Undoing
headline.print_headline: Health Care Success for Midwest Co-op Proves Its Undoing

docs.abstract: Failure of CoOportunity Health raises questions about the viability of some 23 nonprofit cooperatives created under the Affordable Care Act to generate competition for traditional insurers; organization became a victim of its own success, attracting 120,000 customers in Iowa and Nebraska that brought with them an unexpectedly high level of health costs; CoOportunity customers are now scrambling to find new insurance.
docs.snippet: The insolvency of CoOportunity Health raised the question of whether a major Affordable Care Act experiment in holding down insurance costs was in trouble beyond Iowa and Nebraska.

docs.lead_paragraph: Government aid to low-income workers has increased, but those without jobs, who are in the direst straits, are receiving scant attention, experts say.

headline.main: Aid to Needy Often Excludes the Poorest in America
headline.print_headline: A Gaping Hole in the Safety Net

docs.abstract: Experts say government aid to people with incomes that are one-half to two times the poverty level has increased since 1983, but to those with incomes less than that it has diminished; shift reflects more conservative political environment and response to broader economic forces like globalization, advancing technology and workers' weakened bargaining strength.
docs.snippet: Government aid to low-income workers has increased, but those without jobs, who are in the direst straits, are receiving scant attention, experts say.
